stylometry: Data mining takes raw data, standardizes it, and organizes it so it may be useful to an organization. An example of data mining would be a data cluster analysis. To perform a data cluster analysis, first we would need to standardize the data in order to assign more uniform and simplified values to a set of data, such as a list of colleges. Then, we would use the Euclidean distance formula to find the squared distances (differences) between the colleges. After assigning these numbers, we can decide which colleges would be cluster centers, or the most "average" colleges we can relate the other colleges to. Finally, we assign each college to one of these "average" college cluster centers. Data mining is important in business because it can take information that a company has from it's operations, competitors, product performance, and etc. and organize it in a useful form to help make important management decisions.
